<h2 id="cached-data-loaders">Cached Data Loaders</h2>

<p>Jupyter notebooks are great for exploratory data analysis for many reasons.
One major of which is their persistent state between code execution: You
can load your data once and then iteratively perform all sorts of
modifications / visualizations without having to reload your data over the
network.</p>

<p>Sometimes, however, thatâ€™s still not enough: If your network connection is
slow or the dataset youâ€™re trying to analyze particular large or you need
to restart your kernel frequently for whatever reason, data loading can
become a real pain.</p>

<p>To this, Iâ€™ve found myself using cached data loading more and more frequently
in recent times. Hereâ€™s how this may look like in practice:</p>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">_cached_data_loader</span><span class="p">(</span>
